    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-08T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-08T17:00:00-05:00" n="614"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d614">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">832.61333/11–844: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at São Paulo</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cross</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">São Paulo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-08T19:00:00-03:00"
                            >November 8, 1944—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 9:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>147. Dependable sources of coffee information believe that if the OPA made a
                    definite statement that coffee prices would not be increased as long as the war
                    lasted in Europe or in Asia Brazilian prices would return within the United
                    States ceilings and that ample coffee would be forthcoming to supply United
                    States needs. Increase in price would help only large growers, middlemen and
                    speculators and encourage greatly increased plantings of coffee.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cross</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
